  <h1>Hobart Commercial Dishwasher Repair — Los Angeles &amp; Southern California</h1>

  <p>Hobart has been manufacturing commercial dishwashers in Troy, Ohio since 1897 — the brand that defined the commercial dishwasher category and still holds the largest installed base of any commercial dishwasher manufacturer in the United States. In SoCal's food service ecosystem, virtually every high-volume kitchen operation runs Hobart at some point in its equipment history: LAUSD school cafeterias, UCLA dining, Cedars-Sinai, the Westin and Marriott banquet dishrooms, stadium concession operations, and the full spectrum of independent restaurants from Koreatown to the Westside.</p>

  <p>One thing operators often ask: <em>Hobart Service Corporation has its own LA office — why call an independent company?</em> It's a fair question. Hobart Corp's own service network is large and well-resourced. The reasons operators choose independent service typically come down to scheduling availability, response time for non-warranty work, and cost structure. We dispatch same-day on Hobart failures throughout the SoCal market. For operators who need their machine running before the dinner rush and can't wait for a next-day appointment slot, we're the call.</p>

  <p>$120 commercial diagnostic applied to the repair. Call <strong>{phone}</strong>.</p>

  <h2>Hobart Commercial Dishwasher Product Lines</h2>

  <h3>LXeR / LXEH Series — Undercounter Dishwashers</h3>
  <p>Hobart's LXeR and LXEH undercounter dishwashers are the high-temperature workhorse for bars, small restaurants, and café operations throughout SoCal. The LXeR uses a chemical sanitizing final rinse; the LXEH uses a built-in electric booster heater to achieve 180°F final rinse temperature for high-temp sanitization without chemical sanitizer. This distinction matters for health code compliance — LA County Environmental Health inspectors verify sanitization method and temperature on every inspection.</p>
  <p>The LXEH booster heater is the most common service call on this series in the LA market. The booster runs hot water to 180°F in a compact heat exchanger — in LA's hard water zones (250–350 ppm TDS across most of the city), scale accumulates on the booster element at an accelerated rate. An LXEH showing low final rinse temperature almost always has a scaled booster element as the primary or contributing cause. Hobart's ScrubCycle feature — an extended wash cycle for heavily soiled loads — puts additional thermal demand on the booster; machines running frequent ScrubCycles in hard water environments scale faster than machines on standard cycles.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> LXER-1, LXEH-1, LXER-2, LXEH-2, LXeR (current series)</p>

  <h3>AM / AMS Series — Door-Type / Hood Dishwashers</h3>
  <p>Hobart's AM series door-type machines are the volume standard for mid-size restaurant kitchens, hotel room service operations, and institutional cafeteria lines throughout SoCal. The AMS adds a SmartWash sensor system that adjusts cycle parameters based on load soil level — reducing water and chemical consumption on lighter loads while maintaining wash performance on heavily soiled racks. The AM series uses Hobart's hood-sensing door mechanism: the hood must fully close and seal before the cycle initiates, and the door switch is a frequent failure point in high-volume kitchen environments where hoods are operated hundreds of times per shift.</p>
  <p>The AM series runs both high-temp (with booster) and chemical sanitizing configurations. In SoCal institutional kitchens — school cafeterias, hospital food service — the high-temp configuration is standard because it eliminates the chemical sanitizer inventory and dispenser management. The booster heater scaling pattern is the same as on the LXeR: LA water accelerates scale accumulation, and the P1/P2 temperature error codes that result from scaled elements or failing thermistors are the most common Hobart service call we receive in this market.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> AM14, AM15, AM15T, AMS14, AMS15, AM-Advansys</p>

  <h3>CL / CLe Series — Conveyor Dishwashers</h3>
  <p>Hobart CL series conveyor dishwashers are the workhorse of high-volume SoCal food service — hotel banquet dishrooms, university dining, hospital cafeterias, and stadium/venue concession operations. The CLe adds energy recovery technology that captures heat from the exhaust vapor and uses it to pre-heat incoming water, reducing energy consumption. Conveyor machines are significantly more complex than undercounters or door-type machines: multiple wash and rinse zones, conveyor drive systems, curtains between zones, and larger booster heater assemblies all introduce more potential failure points.</p>
  <p>The spray curtains between zones — fabric curtains that separate the pre-wash, wash, rinse, and final rinse zones — are a maintenance item that gets overlooked in most PM programs. When curtains develop holes or tears, zones cross-contaminate: pre-wash water migrates into the wash zone, reducing wash water temperature and pH. In a high-volume hotel or stadium dishroom, a torn curtain can compromise sanitization across the entire conveyor run before it's detected. We inspect curtains on every CL series service call.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> CL64e, CL44e, CLeR, CL-44, CL-64, CL-Advansys series</p>

  <h3>FT / FTeR Series — Flight-Type Dishwashers</h3>
  <p>Hobart FT series flight-type dishwashers are the highest-capacity commercial dishwashers — machines that don't use racks at all, instead moving dishes on a continuous conveyor belt through the wash system. These are found in LA's largest food service operations: the central production kitchens for LAUSD, the main dishrooms at major hotel properties, SoFi Stadium and Kia Forum, and large institutional cafeterias. Flight-type machines are engineering-intensive and require specialized service knowledge. The FTeR adds a vapor energy recovery system. Conveyor drive chain tension, zone curtain integrity, and booster heater performance under high continuous load are the primary service issues.</p>
  <p><strong>Models:</strong> FT900, FT1000, FTeR-66, FTeR-83, FT-Advansys series</p>

  <h2>Hobart Error Codes — P1, P2, and What They Mean in LA</h2>

  <p>Hobart's AM and conveyor series machines display error codes on the digital control panel. The temperature-related codes are the most common in SoCal:</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Code</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Common SoCal Cause</th><th>First Action</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>P1</strong></td>
        <td>Wash tank temperature below minimum setpoint — wash heater not maintaining temperature</td>
        <td>Wash tank heater element scaled or failing; thermistor drift; contactor failure</td>
        <td>Check wash tank temperature against spec (150°F minimum for high-temp), inspect heater element for scale, test thermistor resistance</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>P2</strong></td>
        <td>Booster heater temperature below minimum — final rinse not reaching 180°F</td>
        <td>Booster element scaled from LA hard water; booster thermistor failure; contactor not firing</td>
        <td>Descale booster first, measure final rinse temperature at rack surface with thermometer, test booster element continuity</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>P3</strong></td>
        <td>Rinse temperature sensor fault</td>
        <td>Thermistor open circuit or out-of-range resistance; lime scale coating on probe</td>
        <td>Clean probe surface, measure thermistor resistance against temp chart, replace if out of spec</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Low Wash Temp</strong></td>
        <td>Wash water below 150°F — dishes not being cleaned to standard</td>
        <td>Dirty wash tank heater element, stuck thermostat, high soil load overwhelming heating capacity</td>
        <td>Check wash tank element, verify thermostat setpoint, assess soil load vs cycle selection</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Low Rinse Temp</strong></td>
        <td>Final rinse below 180°F — sanitization not achieved</td>
        <td>Scaled booster heater (primary cause in LA), low incoming water pressure, incoming water temp below minimum</td>
        <td>Descale booster, verify incoming hot water ≥120°F, check water pressure at inlet</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p><strong>The P2/Low Rinse Temp pattern in LA specifically:</strong> This is the single most common Hobart service call we handle in the SoCal market. The sequence is predictable — P2 or Low Rinse Temp appears, operator or previous technician replaces the booster thermistor, code returns within weeks. The root cause is a scaled booster element, not the thermistor. The thermistor is reading accurately; the booster element is physically intact but its surface is coated with calcium carbonate that insulates it from the water. Descaling the booster (not replacing the thermistor) is the correct first intervention. We always descale and verify final rinse temperature before recommending any parts replacement on P2 calls.</p>

  <h2>LA Hard Water and Hobart Machines</h2>

  <p>Hobart's engineering documentation assumes incoming water hardness in a normal range. Los Angeles municipal water — particularly in the areas served by the Metropolitan Water District's blended sources — commonly runs 250–350 ppm total dissolved solids. Some areas of the San Gabriel Valley and South Bay exceed 400 ppm. At these hardness levels, the standard annual descaling schedule that works in softer-water markets is insufficient.</p>

  <p>Our recommended maintenance intervals for Hobart machines in the LA market:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>LXeR / LXEH undercounters:</strong> Monthly booster descaling, quarterly full system descale</li>
    <li><strong>AM / AMS door-type:</strong> Monthly booster descaling, quarterly wash tank descale, bi-annual full inspection</li>
    <li><strong>CL / CLe conveyor:</strong> Quarterly full descale of all wash and rinse zones, monthly spray arm inspection and cleaning, semi-annual curtain inspection and replacement</li>
    <li><strong>FT flight-type:</strong> Quarterly full descale, monthly spray nozzle inspection, semi-annual comprehensive PM</li>
  </ul>

  <p>For high-volume Hobart installations — hotel banquet dishrooms, large institutional cafeterias, stadium operations — we recommend and install inline water softeners on the dishwasher feed line. A properly sized softener dramatically reduces scale accumulation, extends element life, and reduces descaling labor over a 12-month period. The ROI calculation almost always favors softener installation for machines running 8+ hours daily in LA water.</p>

  <h2>Who Runs Hobart in SoCal</h2>

  <p><strong>Institutional food service</strong> is the dominant Hobart segment in the LA market. LAUSD's central production kitchen system, UC and CSU campus dining facilities, and hospital cafeterias throughout the county run Hobart as the standard dishwasher platform. These operations need HACCP-compliant sanitization documentation, which means final rinse temperature records matter — a Hobart running low rinse temperature is a compliance issue, not just a performance issue.</p>

  <p><strong>Hotel banquet operations</strong> in the Beverly Hills, Santa Monica, and Downtown LA hotel corridors typically run Hobart CL or FT series in their main dishrooms. A banquet dishroom failure on an event day — a sold-out wedding, a corporate dinner, an awards show — is a catastrophic operational event. We carry CL series conveyor parts specifically for this segment and prioritize hotel banquet calls.</p>

  <p><strong>Restaurant kitchens</strong> across the full price spectrum run Hobart AM and LXeR units. From neighborhood Korean BBQ in Koreatown to Michelin-starred kitchens in West Hollywood, Hobart door-type and undercounter machines are present. In busy restaurant environments, the AM series runs 12–16 hours daily — the maintenance intervals that apply in a school cafeteria (5 hours/day) don't apply here. Restaurant Hobart machines in LA need more frequent PM than the standard schedule suggests.</p>

  <h2>Hobart vs. Hobart Service Corporation — Understanding Your Options</h2>

  <p>Hobart Corporation operates its own service division with a Los Angeles office. For equipment under active Hobart warranty, routing service through Hobart Corp is the appropriate channel to maintain warranty coverage. For out-of-warranty service, operators have the choice between Hobart Corp's service network and independent companies like ours.</p>

  <p>Factors operators consider when choosing independent service for out-of-warranty Hobart equipment:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Scheduling flexibility:</strong> Same-day availability for emergency calls without entering a service request queue</li>
    <li><strong>Pricing structure:</strong> Independent diagnostics ($120 applied to repair) vs. Hobart Corp's service call structure</li>
    <li><strong>Response time:</strong> For a dinner service emergency at 3pm, same-day dispatch matters more than brand affiliation</li>
    <li><strong>Parts availability:</strong> We source OEM Hobart parts through the same parts distribution network</li>
  </ul>

  <p>For Hobart equipment under active warranty, we advise operators to route service through Hobart Corp to maintain coverage. For out-of-warranty machines — and most Hobart machines in active SoCal service are past the standard one-year warranty — independent service is a legitimate and often faster option.</p>

  <h2>Recent Hobart Service Calls</h2>

  <h3>"AM15T — P2 error, third technician visit, hotel kitchen Century City"</h3>
  <p>Hobart AM15T door-type, P2 error returning despite two previous service visits — first visit replaced the booster thermistor, second visit replaced it again. We arrived to find the booster element coated in approximately 4mm of calcium carbonate scale — the element was electrically functional but thermally insulated from the water. Final rinse temperature was measuring 156°F at the rack surface. Performed full booster descale with Hobart-approved descaler, verified element surface clean, retested — final rinse at 183°F, P2 cleared. Installed inline water softener on the dishwasher feed line. No P2 recurrence in 5 months of follow-up. Three service visits charging for thermistor replacements when the fix was descaling.</p>

  <h3>"CL64e conveyor — low wash temp, torn curtain, UCLA dining facility"</h3>
  <p>Hobart CL64e conveyor showing low wash temperature and dishes coming out with residue. Found two issues on arrival: the curtain between the pre-wash and wash zones had a 6-inch tear, allowing pre-wash water to migrate backward into the wash zone and diluting wash water temperature and chemistry. Also found the wash tank heater element partially scaled. Replaced the curtain assembly, descaled the wash tank element, verified wash zone temperature at 160°F and final rinse at 182°F across the full conveyor run. Inspected all remaining curtains — found two additional curtains showing wear at the corners. Replaced preventively. Briefed facility manager on curtain inspection protocol: quarterly visual check, replacement when any tear or gap appears.</p>

  <h3>"LXEH — not sanitizing, health inspection pending, restaurant Mid-Wilshire"</h3>
  <p>Called the morning of a scheduled LA County health inspection. LXEH undercounter showing normal cycle completion but final rinse temperature measuring 162°F on the operator's surface thermometer — 18 degrees below the 180°F NSF 3 sanitization standard. Booster element scaled, reducing heat transfer efficiency. Descaled the booster element, verified final rinse temperature at 184°F within 45 minutes. Restaurant passed inspection that afternoon. The operator had been using the machine normally for three months since the last service visit without monitoring final rinse temperature. Final rinse temperature should be verified weekly with a calibrated thermometer — not assumed to be correct because the machine completes cycles.</p>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <p><strong>Can you service Hobart dishwashers that are under active warranty?</strong><br>
  For machines under active Hobart warranty, service should be routed through Hobart Service Corporation to maintain warranty coverage. We service out-of-warranty Hobart equipment. If you're unsure of your warranty status, check the unit's installation date and compare it against Hobart's standard one-year parts and labor warranty from date of installation.</p>

  <p><strong>My Hobart is showing a P2 error — what does that mean?</strong><br>
  P2 indicates the booster heater failed to raise the final rinse water to the minimum sanitizing temperature (typically 180°F). In LA's hard water environment, the most common cause is a scaled booster element — the element is electrically functional but its surface is coated with calcium carbonate that prevents efficient heat transfer. Before any parts replacement, the booster should be descaled and final rinse temperature tested. If the temperature normalizes after descaling, no parts are needed. Call {phone} for same-day diagnosis.</p>

  <p><strong>How often should Hobart dishwashers be descaled in Los Angeles?</strong><br>
  Monthly booster descaling minimum for undercounters and door-type machines in LA's water. Quarterly full-system descale for conveyor machines. These intervals are more frequent than Hobart's standard recommendations because LA water hardness (250–350+ ppm TDS) accelerates scale accumulation significantly compared to national averages.</p>

  <p><strong>Do you carry OEM Hobart parts?</strong><br>
  Yes. We source OEM and verified compatible Hobart parts through the standard commercial parts distribution network. Common parts — booster elements, thermistors, wash pump motors, door switches, curtain assemblies, chemical dispenser pumps, and spray arm assemblies — are stocked or available same-day.</p>

  <p><strong>What is your diagnostic fee for Hobart commercial equipment?</strong><br>
  $120 commercial diagnostic, applied directly to the repair cost when you proceed.</p>

  <p><strong>Do you service all Hobart dishwasher series?</strong><br>
  Yes — LXeR and LXEH undercounters, AM and AMS door-type machines, CL and CLe conveyor dishwashers, and FT and FTeR flight-type systems. Conveyor and flight-type service is available throughout the SoCal hotel, institutional, and venue corridor.</p>

